title: For Sale:  Sig Sauer P290 RS
location: Avon Park, FL, Florida, United States
postcontent:
I have for sale a Sig Sauer P290, 9mm handgun.  I acquired this pistol in a trade here on Armslist.  The pistol has factory night sights, and includes the box with manual, lock, etc.  The Sig laser is included and attached with the caveat explained below.

The pistol includes two 6 round magazines and two 8 round extended magazines.  As you can see on the target photo, which was shot at 10 yards, the pistol is very accurate.  The trigger pull is long but smooth and I had no trouble keeping a steady point of aim through the trigger squeeze.  I was very pleased with the accuracy.

I am selling the pistol for one reason.  The grip of this pistol is a bit longer front to back than most other pistols.  For some reason the grip of this pistol is just not at all comfortable for me.  It's solidly constructed, accurate, the night sights glow brightly, and it has functioned flawlessly when I've shot it.  It just doesn't feel good in my hand and I fidget with my grip...it's not for me.

Now to the laser.  The laser works well, it's bright, and turns on and off easily.  During my range sessions I noticed that the laser turns off after each round is fired.  I later checked my grip and I found that the thumb of my off hand is on the switch on the left side of the pistol.  The recoil could be turning the laser off, knocking my thumb against the switch, but I haven't had a chance to go out and shoot it one handed since making the discovery of my grip.  The buyer should be aware that you may have to return the laser to Sig for service.

I've also installed rubber Traction Grips and a Galloway Precision stainless steel guide rod.

A copy of your concealed carry permit will be required, as well as both of us signing a sales receipt.  I will ship the firearm from my FFL to yours if you wish.

title: For Sale/Trade:  SVT 40
postcontent:
For sale is an SVT 40. It has VERY strong rifling and a bore like a mirror. The gas system looks factory new, which is rare for 72 year old rifle that shot corrosive ammo during the war. The stock is a Naval/marine stock as it has a sling loop integrated into the buttstock much like a Mosin. The fact that it is a naval rifle may account for how good a shape the internals are. Naval infantry and the marines did fight the Germans on land, however it was to a much lesser extent than the Red Army itself. The serial number stamped into the stock matches that of the rifle. The stock is a deep Russian red, as it was during the war. The wood does show signs of its age with various scratches attained over time, but such is to be expected of a surplus rifle. There are NO cracks what so ever. The metal pieces are in great shape with its finish still intact with hardly any wear. The bolt is a plum color due to the cleaning solvents the Russians used, but this is common and does not affect the function. The muzzle brake is that of the Early period, as it has several line ports rather than two big ports like that on the AVT40. 

You will never find an SVT in this shape that isn't in a museum. In fact, you won't see any new ones imported unless you're in Canada, as Clinton put an end to that in the 90s. The rifle does have some electric penciling of serial numbers in spots as the Russians tended to force match these after the war. If it was not, I would be asking much more. The one that isn't is the one I'm keeping! 


You can have a piece of history, and the honor to say you own a rifle that is extremely rare, and sought after.

As far as price goes, if I get what I ask, I will be willing to travel, any lower and I'm not leaving Columbus.  It is more than a fair price, Gunbroker and other SVTs on Armslist will show you that. 

One mag included, maybe some ammo if the deal is right.  Must be legally able to own this, will ask for ID.


Detailed pictures by request.

title: For Sale:  1973 Colt Lawman MK III 4" .357 .38 Target grips, exc. cond.
postcontent:
This gun gun has a very crisp, bright blue finish & has the desirable factory target grips.  I've only fired 18 rounds of .38 through the gun & it shoots great in both double & single action.  The lock up is tight, timing is right on, and the trigger is just what you'd expect from a vintage Colt.  The finish is in excellent condition with only a few very small spots on the frame.  I'd say it's over 95%, and you don't see fit & finish like this on most of today's revolvers.  The wood is in excellent shape as well with only one real noticeable mark on the bottom.  I'd say the grips are at 90% +. You won't find a revolver over 30 yrs old in this nice of shape very often.

If you're thinking about buying a new 357 you owe it to yourself to check out one of these vintage Colts. There's a reason people say, "They don't make em like this any more"; and it's the same reason this generation of Colt wheel guns continue to go up in value year after year.

Face to face transactions only.  I'd prefer to sell, but if you have a trade to offer, please give me the details of your offer when you contact me.  Thanks.

title: For Sale:  3 screw Ruger Blackhawk Convertable 45LC/45ACP
postcontent:
Ruger Blackhawk 45Colt Convertible w/ 45 ACP Cylinder
This is a 3-screw (or "Old Model," as they later came to be called) Ruger SA revolvers are based on the same simple design. They were, and still are, perhaps the best single action revolver ever designed. They are loaded with the hammer in the half-cock notch and properly carried with the hammer down on an empty chamber.

The typical 3-screw Blackhawk (so called because of the three screws in the side of the frame) was a blued steel revolver built on a flat top frame roughly the same size as a Colt SAA. The one piece Western-style grip frame is made of aluminum alloy, as is the ejector rod housing. It has two piece walnut grips. The hammer and trigger springs are coil springs, much easier to adjust and more durable than the flat springs used in the Colt SAA. The 3-screw Blackhawk is a simple action, and one that is easy on which to work.

Great bore, holster wear but still a great looking gun in great condition with both cylinders!

postcontent:
Cleaning out some footlockers, and getting rid of survival gear that I no longer need.  $30.00, plus shipping (if you can't meet me in Conyers, GA).  Shipping is $10.00, lower 48.

*Blizzard Survival Blanket.  Not the cheap Mylar thermal blankets; these retail at $30.00 new, and are great for a BoB or GHB.  They're similar in concept to a thermal blanket, but are multi-layered, and work very well.  Package shows wear from being carried in a backpack, but the bag is still in original packaging, and has never even been opened.
*Ballistic Goggles.  Identical to those issued to US forces in OIF/OEF.  Tan frames, and 2 sets of lenses (clear and dark).  They've been work extensively, and the lenses have some scratches, but you can still see through them fine, and they offer great protection.  You may have seen the ads for these awhile back; they stop a load of #8 shot from a 12-Gauge.  Not bad!
*2x 2-qt collapsible canteens.  Used, but in good shape.
*4x Chemical lights.  Orange and Red.
*Old-style goose-neck GI flashlight.  Works fine, has multi-colored lenses.  Handle is wrapped in duct tape, but not as a repair; just a good place to store some emergency tape!
*Padded kidney-pad from a Camelback Assault Pack.  ACU, with waist strap.  It's for your typical 3-day pack, but I've used my identical OD Green one on an Alice pack, and it'll work with a MOLLE ruck, as well; just use some paracord to lash it where you need it.
*Miscellaneous odds and ends; a couple sewing kits, some "caution tape" (very strong, and works great for lashing), GI Issue strap cutter, water purification packets, and other stuff)

Price is based on 1/4th the combined retail cost of a new pair of Ballistic goggles and the Blizzard Survival Blanket (goggles cost me $90 new, and the blanket is $30 new).  As mentioned several times, most items are used (or at least have been lugged around, so they show some wear).  Ask any questions you like BEFORE you buy.  Also, PLEASE DO NOT GO OFF OF THE PICTURE; the items in the picture are the same as those listed above, but I sold a couple items shown in the picture.
